\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid8934373\charrsid1901768 Interview conducted 18 July 2003, Leamington Spa
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 If we could go back to the beginning. You were born in 1922?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 That\rquote s right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And where was that?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\tx3780\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 \tab 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 In {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}England{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Yes. And could you tell me about your family background? I don\rquote 
t know how far back you remember. Your grandparents, for instance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
Yes. Well, I knew my maternal grandmother very well, as is quite commonly the case. She lived well into her nineties. My maternal grandfather died when my mother was about three months pregnant, so I never knew him, and she
 was devastated by this, because she was greatly attached to him. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 What was his profession, then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 I think that he was a salesperson. It\rquote s a little bit difficult to tell from what I\rquote 
ve read, but he had some kind of business activity, and I had 
heard, at one time, it was to do with boots and shoes - but the description gets vague. What I am clear about is that the family was Methodist, and my grandmother had converted to Methodism because of my grandfather. I don\rquote 
t know what her religion had been before. But what I do know is that she was \endash  although I didn\rquote t discover this until, I think, she\rquote d died, and we looked at her passport \endash 
 she was of German origin, and she actually came over, as a child, to the Luton area, where her family were all involved in hat-making. And then she moved into {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}London
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} on that wave of people moving in, as Ray Pahl has described. So that was quite interesting. But, not surprisingly, given her generation, she concealed her Germanness as much as possible, and her Engl
ish was very good - she must have been very young when she came - except for one or two words which we used to laugh about. So she had four children \endash 
 two sons and then two daughters. My mother was quite close in succession to my uncles, I think, then there was a gap, and then there was - the other sister was an afterthought. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And that sister was the one that was \'93kept single\'94
. My mother always said that my grandmother chased all the suitors from the door, because she wanted, as the Italians would say, \'93a stick for her old age\'94
. So that youngest aunt, whom I knew best - because she lived with my grandmother, and latterly they lived not far away - she was an elementary schoolteacher, and a superintendent of her Methodist Sunday School, and a very dedicated p
erson. My mother had been trained as a teacher, in a college in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}South London{\*\xmlclose}, the name of which I forget, but I think it was The Methodist College. I\rquote 
ve a wonderful photograph of the solid ranks of women in Edwardian clothes. So that\rquote s what I roughly know about my maternal side of my ancestors. I might know more if you wanted to probe me, but I think that\rquote ll do for now. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 On my father\rquote s side it\rquote 
s much more complex, and rather romantic, and one doesn\rquote t know which is truth and which is falsehood. (LAUGHS) I\rquote d always thought they were Hungarian in origin. I knew they\rquote d drifted across Europe and finished up in the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}United Kingdom{\*\xmlclose}. It transpires, I think, that they were German. The uncle that one knew about was in fact, it seems, a German in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Hungarian Court{\*\xmlclose} 
\endash  whatever that was. But was it the Austro-Hungarian [court]? - my history is very weak at that part of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Europe{\*\xmlclose}. And I think there was a religious difference with the Court, and he left, an
d he went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Italy{\*\xmlclose}, where it is said he fought with Garibaldi \endash  true or false \endash 
 but you can see the romance issue. It is also said, and possibly truly, that the castle which the family had had, which is to say my grandparents\rquote  preceding generation, or 
some part of it, was the castle in Hungary which General Horthy, was that his name? - the military dictator who took charge of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Hungary{\*\xmlclose}
 not long before the War - offered it back to my Uncle Fritz. Who, wise man that he was, who was then currently a professor in Harvard, and I occasionally saw after he\rquote 
d come back home, and with a big picture of him on the wall, he refused. So the last I knew of him, he was living in Ealing. But he was always held up as the important paternal ancestor. He must have been a brother of my father\rquote 
s mother, I would guess. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
They had a very chequered career, that family, and my sister knows much more about it because she and her husband have been doing some [research]. I\rquote ve not really kept up with what they\rquote ve found out. But the story is that they were \endash 
 and I think this is true \endash  they were those sort of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Manchester{\*\xmlclose} industrialists, who sprung up, but they also had business involvements in various parts of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}
Northern England{\*\xmlclose}, and moved around. But then the story is that my grandfather \endash  my father\rquote s father \endash  drank the business away, so that it was always said to be typically \'93clogs to clogs in three generations\'94
, although I don\rquote t think they began quite as clogs! My grandmother was living in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Edinburgh{\*\xmlclose}, I think, with two sisters \endash  Leah and Rachael \endash  who never married. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 When she married my grandfather, whom I never knew, James Petrie 
\endash  because I didn\rquote t know either of my grandfathers \endash  who was of a Scottish family, and very strict, my father would tell me that there was a Sunda
y post in those days, and the post that came in on a Sunday was put on the mantelpiece and nobody was allowed to touch it until Monday. So he had a touch of the John Knox or something! But I suspect that my grandmother\rquote 
s family had been - well, I don\rquote t know what they were. Certainly one of her children went off to be a Catholic nun, but that doesn\rquote 
t signify. I think my grandmother had seven children who survived, of whom my father was the fifth, I think. He had a rough childhood, and the exciting things he 
told us was how he remembered having to run across the moors to tell the vicar to toll the church bell for the death of Queen Victoria, and this seemed to be extremely romantic to us! In any case, so they were very }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 d\'e9class\'e9}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768  and up and down, and full of \'e9migr\'e9s on the one side.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 So did any of those uncles or aunts have some interesting careers, or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Erm \'85 well, I don\rquote 
t know much about them. Rita was the one that stayed at home, as unmarried. Phyllis went to be a Catholic nun.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 This is on your mother\rquote s side now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 No, this is my father\rquote s.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Oh, I see. Because there was another that one stayed at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 There\rquote s another one stayed. But on both sides of the family, that pattern of keeping a girl in the home, there it was, you kn
ow, black and white. So I was just thinking of my father\rquote s family, because I\rquote d been talking about him. My Auntie Eunice, who was slightly older than him, had a career as a theosophist \endash  if you could call it a career \endash 
 I mean, that is what she did, and she 
was out with Annie Besant in India, and things like that. So she was quite clearly defined, and was an independent woman, and she had this strong belief system. And she used to come and see us about once a year, and I really loved her, I thought she was r
eally nice. And my father had, in some way, defended her when there were difficulties in the family, I don\rquote t know what they were \endash  I was never told. But I don\rquote 
t know that I know what jobs any of the others had. It's no good, I can't say.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 On my mother\rquote s sid
e, her older brother was a Minister, first of all a Methodist Minister, then he migrated to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Canada{\*\xmlclose} and became a Free Church Minister there, and in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Nova Scotia
{\*\xmlclose} was where I knew him to be \endash  {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Prince Edward Island{\*\xmlclose}. He used to come over every other y
ear or something, to see his mother, and I would always meet with him then, along with the rest of the family. The younger brother, his name was Sydney, then there was Bert, and Bert went into the Income Tax and became a Chief Inspector of Taxes, so they 
moved around the country quite a lot, as they moved them round so they didn\rquote t get locked up in the local criminal gangs or something \endash  whatever the story was! And he finished up in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}
. Then my mother was an elementary schoolteacher, and her younger sister was an elementary schoolteacher, and they were the first generation of people to do anything like professional, if that\rquote s the right word to use. So they\rquote 
re a bit clearer because I was closer to them.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 \tab  And what was your father\rquote s occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
My father had a chequered career, but I think he would describe himself as a Company Director. But when I first was aware, he was working for a mantle manufacturer, and doing a lot of travelling \endash  selling coats and stuff \endash 
 so whether he was really a rep, I don\rquote 
t quite know. Then, at some point, I think it must have been in the thirties, he bought a small printing works, which he wanted to run on certain rather clear non-exploitative principles. But that finally folded. And then I think he acquired anot
her, smaller, lithographic place, which also finally went completely bust. And when I asked him how this all happened, he said the firm was over-capitalised and didn\rquote t explain it any more than that. He had wanted my sister and I \endash  I\rquote 
ve just got one sister, no brothers \endash  to go into the business, and he used to have us go in in the holidays. And I was very happy to work in the office and do all manner of things, but my sister wouldn\rquote 
t do anything except work in the Binding Room, which was the simplest of all the tasks it might have been possible to do in a 1930s printing works. So my father was very upset when I said, \'93I\rquote m sorry, I didn\rquote t want to go into the business
\'94, because what I saw of being in business just turned me right off. You know, the cheats you had to get up to and one thing and another, it didn\rquote t appeal to me, so I got out.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Were you close to him, your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Yes. I\rquote 
ve been thinking about this recently. He had a greater understanding, I felt, of me, than my mother did. She was a rather nervous person when it came to the bit. She had a very good singing voice, and she had it trained, her parents arranged for that, but
 she didn\rquote t really sing in public, and my father said that she was always so nervous, she couldn\rquote t really let go, you know, and sing as she would in the drawing room. I don\rquote t know what made me think of that!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 You were talking about being close to [your father].
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Oh yes, who I was closer to, yes, that\rquote s right. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
So I felt that my mother, I felt her as a bit of a dragon, and she felt her mother as a bit of a dragon. She always used to say that she broke things in Granny\rquote s house, which she didn\rquote 
t in her own house. So there was a certain authoritarianness in both of them, but it isn\rquote t until my very mature years that I realised that, underneath this, which was frightening to me, I suppose, but also I fought agai
nst, was really a very frightened woman and that\rquote 
s helped me to understand a lot more. So that was her. When she got married, which she did in about 1919, she gave up working, and she would never ever go back, except and until the Second World War broke ou
t, and my sister and I were left home by then. And they sent a great SOS for her, \'93We\rquote re desperate for teachers. Will you come back?\'94
 So she went back, and she really enjoyed it. And we were all very glad that she did, because she should have been doing something like that before, something more than - rather constrained.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Do you think she had different hopes of your career than your father did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Well, I should explain that both of them were Feminists, as I mentioned earlier. And my father was mi
litant, he was a Suffragist, and he was going to meetings and would disrupt and get thrown out. My mother wouldn\rquote t have any of that. She was much more mild, she wouldn\rquote t, didn\rquote 
t take any direct action, but she would go along to the meetings which he then got thrown out of. He cut the telephone wires on Hampstead Heath at one time, and there\rquote 
s still a newspaper cutting about that, and we thought it was a wonderful thing to have done. And the shears he\rquote d used \endash  I don\rquote t know why he used shears, but I suppose it was something to do with the difficulty of the job \endash 
 he buried in my maternal grandmother\rquote s garden \endash  his mother-in-law\rquote s garden \endash  and she was very, very upset. I don\rquote t know why he let her know! But (LAUGHS) in any case, that\rquote s what he did, and he was nev
er apprehended for this. It was in the newspaper, just one line of many things. So I had these parents with a clear idea about the liberation of women, although that\rquote s not what the latter day Feminists would have called it. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 But the first consequence was 
that they insisted upon giving us the same education that we would have had, had we been boys. And this wasn\rquote t, as it can be in some families, because there weren\rquote t any boys, it was because that\rquote s what they would have done, even if we
\rquote d have had brothers. So they made efforts and although they didn\rquote 
t really have very much money, they moved into London, from where they were living in Pinner, in Middlesex, which was then in the country, and sent us to the City of London School, which suited me very well. [But
 it] suited my younger sister very badly, and she should have been moved to somewhere else, because she was very into painting, very artistic, not very academic. Under my shadow, because they kept saying to her, \'93Well, Margaret\rquote s doing \'85
 blah, blah, blah\'94. Horrible! So she wasn\rquote t happy, but I was happy there.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 What actually happened to her in the end?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
She, first of all, went nursing, and then she had to give that up because she got manifold illnesses. Then she got a job in the Civil Service, and
 she sat for, and passed, an examination which would have made her a permanent civil servant, and this was greeted by all of us with great joy, because her stickability at doing exams was what she lacked. She\rquote 
d got the wit and all of that. And then, if you please, she was turned down on medical, because she\rquote 
d had a lot of trouble with one of her ears, where she got a middle-ear infection, and there was, of course, no control, no antibiotics, it was before antibiotics, and they said, \'93Every time you get this again, you will be off work, so we\rquote 
re not having you\'94. That\rquote s how it was interpreted. So I think she went on being in the temporary Civil Service, one way and another. There were times when she wasn\rquote t working at all, when she was just being a mother, quit
e long periods, I think, and I can\rquote t be absolutely clear about that. And she still paints, and she paints brilliantly. There will be some of her pictures up, but we haven\rquote t got everything hung up yet.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 So going back to your parents, clearly they were interested - you\rquote 
ve talked about the Feminism - I guess they were also interested in politics more generally, or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
They were not so interested in politics. The other significant thing about them is that they were both Christian Scientists, so I was brought up as a Christian Scientist. And, of course, that\rquote 
s interesting, because Mary Baker Eddy, who founded it, was one of that swathe of American Feminists who were involved in religion in one way and another. So that her teachings, which included se
x equality among other things, obviously reinforced their own Feminist ideas. Which I suspect they\rquote d got separately, but I don\rquote t know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And was there much discussion about religion, or Feminism, in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
Well, we were taken to church, or Sunday School, every week. And we were expected to do - there are readings that Christian Scientists are supposed to do on a daily basis, from the Bible, and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Science and Health}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768  and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Key to the Scriptures}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 , which Mary Baker E
ddy wrote, and is the key thing, and we were expected to read these every morning. So that was a strong, a strong influence, but also an influence of an indirect kind, because the mockery that we got in school, when people knew that we were Christian Scie
ntists \endash  I don\rquote t know how it affected my sister, because she and I didn\rquote t talk about that sort of thing \endash 
 but it certainly made me very sympathetic to downtrodden minorities, and for the Jewish girls who were in the School, who were also particularly - as N
azism grew and so on - were subject to anti-Semitism, and there was a lot of incredible imperialistic racism in the School, among the girls. And I think quite a lot of my attitudes to life come from those experiences of, on the one hand, being accepted by
 
teachers and so on, for the academic work I was able to do, and for passing my exams and sweating on the subjects I was bad at, and so on, and at the same time, feeling like a nothing and a nobody, and also reinforced by the fact that we were really very 
short of money at some periods in the thirties and into the War, so that there were all the usual problems about not having nice clothes or a new uniform, or whatever it was. There was all of that stuff.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 I\rquote m wondering, also, though, whether at home, 
with your mother and father, you would be talking about ideas or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
Good question. With my father, less than my mother. My father had an expansive and adventurous mind, and imaginative, and he also used to get very concerned about issues and talk a
bout them. It was never on the lines of Party politics, that I can recall, but yes, I did have discussions with him, and my mother didn\rquote 
t really seem to get involved in that. She used to stand over my homework when I was younger, and tell me all the things I\rquote d done wrong, and I can remember how delighted I was when I got to do things that she couldn\rquote 
t possibly help me with, and it was a great relief! (LAUGHS) But she was better able to deal with what she\rquote d been taught, and what she\rquote d read, and things like that. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And what about feelings? Could you talk to either of them about feelings and difficulties and so on?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 I think so. Yes. I don\rquote 
t know how much - any feelings that one had, like illnesses that one had, would be referred to the religious base
, you know, and they would talk it through in terms of how one ought to be thinking about it, and knowing the truth, and all the ways that Christian Scientists were supposed to practice. So I think that\rquote 
s how it would be. But they were very supportive and very sympathetic, and my father found my sister extremely difficult, and she was a great buddy of my mother\rquote s, so there was a sort of split like that. But we didn\rquote 
t have great academic type conversations, or political type conversations, except in the principle of Feminism, and I think, you know, exploitation of people was something that he wasn\rquote t very happy about. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
On the other hand, I can remember, once, coming back from school, we used to walk through The Temple, to get the Tube at Holborn or somewhere, and I\rquote 
d seen a couple together, I think it was a Chinese or a Japanese woman, and a European man, and it was very rare in those days, so I went home, and I said, bouncingly, to my mother, \'93It was so nice, I saw this and this and this\'94, you know? She said,
 \'93Oh, well \'85\'94 she didn\rquote 
t think that was very good! (LAUGHS) Very full of problems. So that was a great - put me down rather. And then when I found, later, that the Christian Science Churches were very strictly segregated into black and white, that put me off as well.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 That was much later, that would have been?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 It was, I think, early in the War. I don\rquote t know how I found that out. I don\rquote 
t know quite how I found that out, but I did. I, for some reason, was looking at the Directory \'85 what was it called? Something like the Registrar\rquote s Directory \endash  that\rquote s not the right name \endash 
 and saw that there was this race segregation, and it shocked me, because the teachings that I\rquote d picked up didn\rquote t lead one in that direction at all.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Now, you\rquote ve mentioned sch
ool once or twice, but could we talk a bit about whether there were important influences from the teachers or other people you met at the different schools?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Well, I first of all went to a Dame School, for a little tiny while, learning to do sums on s
lates, but mainly I went to a private primary school in Pinner, where I wasn\rquote 
t very happy. And then we moved into London, and I think I was eight, and my sister five, and we went to the City of London School. And there were important influences there. The 
first form teacher, which had three years in it, was a very kindly woman, and very supportive, and very encouraging, so I remember her favourably. The crisis I had was that they decided they\rquote 
d put me in a form too low, jumped me a year, and that set me bac
k. I did the sciences, and I think both the physics mistress and the chemistry mistress, and botany we did, it was still in those days, they were quite an important influence. The chemistry mistress, in particular, not only because of the chemistry, which
 was fun, but because she was a country dancer, and she was in the England team, and she taught us country dancing after school, and I really enjoyed that, because dancing wasn\rquote 
t something that my family were into. The last Headmistress, Miss Winters, was quite a profound influence. But we were evacuated, and she became, really, more of a colleague, because she gave me great \endash  I was Head Girl \endash 
 and she gave me great responsibility for seeing to the welfare of the girls, and I was supposed to see they weren\rquote t roaming round the Common and so on.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Where was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
In Ashstead, in Surrey. And we were there for a year. And then in the summer holidays, they dropped a bomb, either on Ashstead or nearby, so the school was then removed up to Keighley in Yorkshire. But I\rquote 
d left by that time, and gone to LSE. One of the maths teachers, Miss Page, was a strong influence, and in particular, when it looked as if I might not be able to go to university, because it couldn\rquote t be afforded, she offered to produce some 
money, and I was very struck by this. The other maths teacher, too, I got on well with. The language teachers I didn\rquote t, because I\rquote m a bad linguist.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 You didn\rquote t like humanities?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 No, I suppose I didn\rquote t. I suppose I didn\rquote 
t. I had to do English and all of those things. I really appreciated the German teacher, but I didn\rquote t do it for very long. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Now, this is a school, entirely girls, and all the staff were women, is that right?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 That\rquote s right. That\rquote s right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And what sort of ethos were they presenting, would you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Well, the older ones were people who had graduated from Cambridge or Oxford, without being given a degree. I
\rquote ve later discovered just how badly they were exploited by the City of London Corporation, which was responsible for the School. So, sorry, say your question again?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 I\rquote 
m interested in the ethos. For instance, were they encouraging you, strongly, as girls, to go on to university, and to have careers, or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 They were. There 
were sort of three things that you could do. If you were bright, they pushed you towards Oxford or Cambridge. If you were not too unbright, they pushed you either to secretarial work, or to nursing. So that was about the range. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 I had a little battle
 to get support to go to LSE, because it was neither Oxford nor Cambridge, and I think I may have been the first girl, from the school, to go to LSE. Lots and lots have gone since. Which was interesting, because there was LSE in the City, and the School w
as in the City, but these women were very Oxford and Cambridge themselves, and those were the best places to go, and that\rquote s where the best pupils should go, I suppose.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 It\rquote s particularly interesting because this is always seen as a
 period in which Feminism has ceased to be a public issue, hadn\rquote t it, and yet these institutions for women were going on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 That\rquote s right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 I'm wondering, to what extent you got that kind of old Feminist message there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 \tab Oh, very strongly. The School song began, \'93
Women of England, the heart of the nation, here the full share of our birthright we claim \'85\'94 I now forget, but it goes on like that. \'93Mothers and daughters of England to be \'85\'94 is the final line, but it was, \'93the full share of our birth
right we claim\'94, and that was not talked about so much, as it was the entire ethos of the School. Women were as good as men, you could do what men did, which people didn\rquote t then any more than they do now - but they do now in a way that\rquote 
s completely revoluti
onary to me. So, yes, it was a strong Feminist ethos. But in that quiet period - and it was because partly of that, I suppose, that I was so cross with the New Wave Feminists, for saying or implying there was no Feminism then. I had a few chomping argumen
ts with people about it, and, of course, they recognised, in the end, that they were quite wrong, and people wrote studies showing about these quiet ways in which the Feminist gains of the earlier period were being put into practice \endash 
 which was comforting! It was quite uncomfortable in those days, when the New Movement was developing, because we were called by some \'93the traitor generation\'94
 who got married and had children, and this must have come out of radical Feminism, I suppose, that notion. But for somebody who thought that she\rquote d been brought up as a Feminist, had been Feminist all her life, had claimed her birthright \endash 
 in terms of going to the university \endash  it was very hurtful. (LAUGHS) 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 I can imagine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
So one gets these internal problems. But I was so impressed with what they were doing, this new wave of Feminists, and what they were uncovering, that I didn\rquote 
t have any long-term rancour with them. I learnt such a lot, and it was so valuable to me, so that was a short-lasting difficulty. So that all arose from the ethos of my parents and the School. And they obviously chose the School for these reasons. 

\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 We had nothing to do with the Boys\rquote  School. The Boys\rquote 
 School was a couple of streets away, and I think 
we had to go there to sit some exams, science exams perhaps. The City of London School for Girls was then in Carmelite Street, which is just off the Thames, near Blackfriars. The boys were in a purpose-built school facing the Thames, quite near Blackfriar
s Bridge. The Girls\rquote  School is now in the Barbican, although I haven\rquote t been to see.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Now, thinking of you as a future sociologist, here you were, in the middle of a very fascinating city. I
\rquote m wondering to what extent, as an adolescent, you were able to explore it and see the social variety and so on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Well, I didn\rquote t sort of \'85
 oh, wait a minute! I used to read a lot of Dickens, because if you were in the Science Sixth, you had to read English, so I chose Dickens, because I found he was very interesting, and would note down the streets that he\rquote 
d used in his various novels. So I had that kind of awareness. I can remember stepping over the drunks sometimes, on the way to school, which then was a phenomenon one ceased to see, and fuelled my anger when w
e, again, got people sleeping on the streets. And we were right in the heart of the newspaper world, so I can remember, for example, looking out of the classroom window, and there were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
Evening Standard}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768  vans saying, \'93War, War, War, War\'94 all along them, and 
that really sort of shook me. That was the Spanish War, the Spanish Civil War, and that really alerted me to a lot of the internal European problems, in a way that I perhaps hadn\rquote 
t been before. The one political issue that my parents talked about frequently was about war, and the need to end war. My father had been a pacifist, and he actually got his Conscientious Objector\rquote 
s right not to serve, and for reasons I never really understood, he turned it in and went into the trenches, but he wouldn\rquote t be an offic
er, although they wanted him to be. So that linked up with when the Spanish Civil War broke out. And then, of course, one got to know quite a lot of people who had been, or knew about them. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 [BREAK IN RECORDING]
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Going back to London. What I was par
tly wondering was whether, for instance, did you see the East End, the Jewish area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
Yes, I did. I suppose the first thing to say is that there were Scholarship Girls came to our school, and that was their title, \'93Scholarship Girls\'94, and I noticed, ve
ry quickly, that they all sat in one block together in the form - I think there were three blocks in a typical form room. And I also noticed that, although I couldn\rquote 
t have put it in these words then, but I noticed it, that girls who had professional parents \endash  doctors and lawyers and people \endash  they all tended to sit together. And then I don\rquote 
t know quite who was in the block where I sat, but I had noticed these social gradations. I\rquote ve already mentioned the anti-Semitism. And certainly my father\rquote s little Works,
 where I went to work in the holidays, was in Hackney, and we used to join in the street parties, because he was trying to be a very egalitarian employer. He wanted to share profits, but the workers didn\rquote 
t want to share the risks, and that was a great pain
 to him. But he was very close to the people working there, and the people in the streets around, so I had a very good idea about what the old East End was like. Very partial, very limited, but I knew this was a world apart and quite different. I also was
 involved with the missionary work of the School, which was less concerned with foreign territories than helping out the poor of London, and I used to spend some time in settlements, so I learnt quite a lot about the circumstances of South London.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 They had their own settlement?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 There was a Union of Girls\rquote 
 Schools [which] had a settlement in Peckham, and I stayed there. I worked for the Invalid Children\rquote s Aid Association it was called, which funded people to get holidays out of London. So that th
ose experiences, partly from my family and partly from what came out of school, showed me a number of sides of London I wouldn\rquote t otherwise have seen.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And the area you were living in was where?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 We were living, by the time we were going to the City School, in Palmers Green.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Ah! A suburb, in fact, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 A suburb, yes. That\rquote s right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 What kind of social level would it have been then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
Not as posh as Southgate, but it was still a respectable suburb. And my sister still lives nearby where she was born, and it\rquote s changed beyond all recognition. I keep hearing from her these accounts, the way the shops have changed, but it was a \'93
good\'94 shopping centre. My grandmother lived in Bowes Park, which was just down the hill from The Triangle at Palmers Green, which was an area which had been built in the late part of the 19}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\super\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768  century. The house she lived in - maybe both the houses they\rquote d had built to order, I\rquote 
m not quite certain, there were obviously developments and they acquired them. So, yeah, it was \'85 But I had very little to do with the neighbourhood children, partly because of going to the City every day, to school, partly because we were taken 
to church in a different part of London, so no part of my life really threw me in with kids until I joined the Rangers, I think, and that was the first time I really got to mix with young people from that area.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 To what extent were you brought up to be aware of social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 I don\rquote 
t think one could have been brought up, in the twenties and thirties, without being aware of social class. \'93People like us don\rquote t do things like that\'94.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 You were saying that people had to behave in a way that was appropriate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 That\rquote 
s right. And this was strongly reinforced by the School. We always have to have our hats and gloves on. We couldn\rquote t possibly be seen in the street without our hats and gloves on. And you couldn\rquote t possibly eat in the street, that wasn\rquote 
t allowed at all. Whereas in my family of origin, I suppose it was, \'93People like us don\rquote t do things like that\'94. It came from my mother rather than my father, who\rquote d moved through so many standards of life. In school, they didn\rquote 
t say, \'93Ladies don\rquote t do things like that\'94
, which happened to some of my friends in other schools, but you got a strong impression that there was an appropriate way to behave, and, of course, you were going to be an appropriate person. So it wasn\rquote t discussed, overtly, as a class issue
, [but] it was deep-seated.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
And at one point, you were rather hinting that professionals were regarded differently from yourselves. Were you seen as \'93in trade\'94 or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 I suppose so. I think it was not necessarily being seen as,
 it was the self-assurance and the knowledgeability, and the grasp of a world that was quite out of my vision, that marked them off, because they had access to - and that much I understood then. My father, when he knew that I really wanted to go to univer
sity and they both thought - my parents - thought it would be a good idea, took us, in the course of one touring holiday, around some of the Cambridge colleges, so that we could get a sense of what it was like.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And you felt it was a very different world, is that what you\rquote re saying?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 That\rquote s right, yes. But because I\rquote d been there, I thought, \'93Well, there are real people here!
\'94 (LAUGHS) And it was very interesting.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 So why did you choose LSE?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Because I was, by that time, deeply involved in all sorts of social issues. I wasn\rquote 
t sufficiently interested in science to want to go and be a scientist, in which case one might have headed for Cambridge, and I wasn\rquote t, as you indicated, a strong humanities
 person. But I had, by the time the War broke out, which was my last year of school, [become] very well aware of enormous social differences, and I suppose, at the back of my mind - yes, this is true, I mustn\rquote t forget it \endash 
 that I was going to be a social w
orker. Because there were these sort of jobs in typing, and nursing, and social work, which were possible for girls to do. And that was in my head, because I had been very concerned with the poverty - shocked to the core. And so LSE seemed to be an approp
riate place. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And was there an interval between school and LSE, then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 No, there wasn\rquote 
t. It was my last year at school. As I said, the Headmistress rather used me like another teacher, and I failed Higher School Certificate, which has comforted a lot of young people who\rquote ve done the same thing at \lquote A\rquote 
 levels or something! I really hadn\rquote t conc
entrated on my work because I was so distracted by this whole business of the War and being evacuated, and being expected to do all these extra jobs. And our maths mistress went to pieces. I can remember, she really did go to pieces. She was, all the time
, imagining that we would be having our packs on our backs and fleeing to Wales. She, clearly, had some type of breakdown, so that didn\rquote t help my maths, which was my strong point, really. I can\rquote 
t remember what I passed, but, anyway, I failed the total thing
. And my poor sister passed her General School Certificate, and she says that nobody took any notice of her because they were so upset that Margaret had failed! (LAUGHS) And, nevertheless, the teachers backed me very strongly, and I was tremendously lucky
 to be interviewed by Norah Anstey, who was a great encouragement and, obviously, was a key in my being admitted. I mean, I could have some old - no, I won\rquote t go on! So that was really a great piece of luck.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And what were you applying to read at the LSE?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
Sociology and Social Work. And had it not been for the War, the plan would have been to have stayed for a fourth year to do the Social Policy/Social Work training. As it was, I doubled it up, so I got a concentrated dose of Ginsberg, a bit of Man
nheim, and the people from the Social Science Department who taught rather practical things - about Applied Social Science really. What was the name of that Department? It might have been Social Science, I can\rquote t remember.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 I think there was Social Policy and Social Work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 I think that might be it\rquote s later name, and it was something else when I was there. But never mind.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
It would be interesting if you could say a few more words about people like Ginsberg and Mannheim, that taught you. How did they strike you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
Well, I became a great devotee of Ginsberg, for which I got mocked by latter day sociologists who, after the Shils revolution, because he was thought to be a muddle-headed philosopher. And it\rquote s true, he taught Malthus at second-han
d. But also there was a lot to that guy. But he was totally a theorist.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 When you say, \'93there was a lot to that guy\'94, what was good about him, then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Well, I think he had a very strong character. One of his essays that I liked the best, is one a
bout anti-Semitism, and another one relating to attitude to animals, which was interesting. But when he came down from his theory pedestal and talked about practical things - one thing where he did teach empirical data (mostly he didn\rquote 
t) was about class - 
he did direct us to reading such work as had been done at an empirical level, on class, and I found that interesting. So when I say he was a good guy, I suppose I mean that he was somebody whose values I could appreciate, insofar as I knew what they reall
y
 were. Mannheim I had much less of, because Ginsberg was the fixture during the War. People were rushing off and doing war work. Harold Laski, who had a strong influence on me, was always jumping on a train and going up to London and doing whatever war wo
rk he was doing. And other people disappeared, completely, to Intelligence or wherever they were taken off to. So the staff was a bit attenuated.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 So Mannheim, you didn\rquote t really see much of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Didn\rquote t see very much of Mannheim. And I wasn\rquote t happy with what I read of Mannheim. I didn\rquote 
t click with Mannheim at all.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Why was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 It\rquote s difficult to say now. I\rquote d really have to go back to his works. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 \tab But was there anybody else there that left a strong impression on you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Well, Laski, I mentioned.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 \tab But that\rquote s more politically Laski, would it be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Yes, I suppose so. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 [BREAK IN RECORDING]
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 You were talking about LSE and the people there. I think you\rquote 
ve talked about the sociologists, but what about the people who were teaching social work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 That\rquote s right. And I\rquote ve been trying to remember their names, but I can\rquote 
t. There was a guy called, was it something Chamberlain? There were three people there, and they were all very impressive and I appreciated that. An
d there was this interesting gap between the very philosophical sociological approach of Maurice Ginsberg, and the very distinct approach of Mannheim, and what I was learning in the Social Policy/Social Work area, and that really fired me up as to what I 
wanted to do when I\rquote d graduated. Because I really don\rquote t remember Ginsberg really referring to any empirical [work] - well, there wasn\rquote t very much to refer to, to be quite honest, between kind of, like, \rquote 40 and \rquote 
43, except for the material about class. And t
hen the research that I would learn about in the Social Science Department would be about people who became criminals, people who were very poor, people who had housing problems, categories of people with socially defined problems. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 That was really why I 
finally did the Banbury Study. Because I really thought that we needed some empirical data about how \'93ordinary people\'94 lived \endash 
 not these categories who were presenting social problems. And it seemed to me - I wanted to link with the theoretical ideas. And the gap I just found very upsetting. So if people have called me a theoretically oriented empiricist, or something, that
\rquote s quite pleasing to me, because there were the empiricists who didn\rquote t think about what the data they had, what it had got to do with th
e greater scheme of things. And there were the people who thought about the greater scheme of things who were somewhere up in the air and not anchored. So I decided to work on the anchors, but try not to lose track of the theory, which I didn\rquote 
t address at all formally, because I felt nervous to do that. But it was always there in my head.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Did you have to do practical exercises of some kind for the social work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Yes. I can remember going to a factory in Birmingham - perhaps that was in the Personnel Department. And I
\rquote m now confused between the vac jobs I took to get a bit of money, because I had very scrapey money, and the ones that were placements. I can only clearly remember that Birmingham factory placement. But I can remember working in Metal 
Box for a vac job, and insisting on working the same hours the workers did, because there was a student room where they allocated jobs for students, and they did 8-5 or something pretty poor. But yes, we did have placements.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Now, LSE had moved out to somewhere else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
Well, we were in Cambridge the whole time, yes. Yes, it was quite different from Cambridge, in London, I think, and I\rquote ve never felt that I really belonged to LSE, in the London sense, you know, although I used to go there for seminars later on.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Did you have any contact with the anthropologists at LSE?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 No. Mostly my contact with the anthropologists was the ones at 
Oxford, because after I graduated, I worked in a War Factory for a year, and the idea still was that I was going to train to be a Personnel Manager. But a year in a War Factory as a - whatever they called us - anyway, personnel, taught me that this is not
 a job that I could do. It was too much of an intermediary job, neither the management nor the workers would begin to trust you.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Where was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 That was ROF 52, on the Firth of Clyde, just opposite the Dumbarton Rock.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And as a social experience, how did you find that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 One learnt a lot, working \'85 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 [BREAK IN RECORDING]
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 We were talking about working in the factory on the Clyde.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 That\rquote s right. And it was quite extraordinary. Although I\rquote d worked in factories before, in the 
South-East of England, it was going in with all these - because the Grade 3 Labour Officers worked the same shifts as the workers, so we went in on the same shifts that they went in. It was an altogether new experience. But also, the kind of jobs one was 
given to do. And the person I got on best with was the Communist Shop Steward, and we tended to shut the door and say, \'93Well, what are we going to do about this?\'94
 And I had a close flirtation with Communism at that time because, really, the Labour Party wasn\rquote t impressing me.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Were you politically active, then, at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Yes. I had joined the Labour Party. It may have been before the War broke out, I think it\rquote 
s possible, in Palmers Green. I do remember, I wasn\rquote t impressed, because here I was, terribly young and completely raw, and just joined, and they wanted me to be Secretary of a Branch! So that, you know, I wasn\rquote 
t very active, and I refused that quickly.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 But you were impressed by these Communist Shop Stewards in Scotland?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Well, when I got closer to the Communist Party, I wasn\rquote 
t in the least bit impressed, because the totalitarianism, the ordering about, I fled very quickly. So this particular guy, Mick, I could understand where he was coming from, but you didn\rquote 
t have to be a Communist to do that. He was really concerned with the conditions the workers were working in, and that was what I thought I was there for, but I think the management had somewhat different ideas. But I was the lowest of the low, so it
\rquote s very impressionistic. So in a year I got out. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 So what year are we now? \rquote 44?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Yeah. I graduated in \rquote 43, it was \rquote 
44. And I managed to get my release because I was conscriptable age, to go to work for the Extra-Mural Department of Oxford University. It turned out, I later discovered, that I had undue influence in the Ministry - a long-standing supporter of the WEA wa
s working in whichever Ministry it was, and she thought it was very important, and her daughter \endash  who was a friend of mine \endash  was already in the Extra-Mural Delegacy at Oxford, and she got hold of my file and wrote, \'93Release this woman\'94
 across it, so I learnt, many, many years later! 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
Anyway, I got my release, which was important, and went to work for the Extra-Mural Department at Oxford. The condition was that one had to lecture to the troops as well. And that was an eye-opener as well, because sometimes th
e Education Officer paraded a whole hangar full of people, and sometimes the much more sensitive Education Officer pulled out the few people that were really interested, and you had a very informal session. So that taught me a lot. And in the meantime I w
as teaching the class in Banbury.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Oh, so you went to Banbury pretty soon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 That was where they placed me, it was my parish. From \rquote 
44 onwards I was living in Banbury, because they wanted me to develop the Extra-Mural Education and the Workers\rquote  Education in North Oxfordshire and North Bucks. That was my brief.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 [BREAK IN RECORDING]
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Yes. So you\rquote ve got to Banbury, and you have to develop the extra-mural education.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 That was the idea.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 So that means there wasn\rquote t very much happening in extra-mural education, really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 No. What they were particularly concerned with was the aluminium workers in the NAC, as it was then called 
\endash  ALCAN it became later. They were on three shifts, and they didn\rquote t get any adult education. Banbury was a lit
tle market town and it had expanded, enormously, with the coming of the aluminium factory, and then the War had broken out and the town was so full, it was closed. You had to have permission to go and live there. What the Oxford Extra-Mural people wanted 
was to - and the WEA, because they always worked closely together - was to have education taken to the people who were on the three shifts. And I worked with what was then the Municipal and General Workers\rquote 
 Union, which had Unionised most of those people, and finally got a class which met in both evenings and the afternoons, whereby one could catch - or was it the mornings? I can\rquote 
t remember. But, in any case, I repeated things, so that members of different shifts could come. They worked a night shift, and a back shift, and a day shift.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And what were you teaching them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
Well, sociology, but, in fact, all sorts of things, because one had to negotiate the subject. But with the Banbury people, it was really sociology, because how the Banbury Study beg
an was that I set them off to do a bit of a study of Banbury, the class members, and that was interesting. But I also had to teach things like the British Constitution \endash  fancy that! I can\rquote 
t quite remember what else. But it was sociology of a kind that I was teaching.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 So, now, you got married in 1945, is that right?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Yes, that\rquote s right. Like a lot of other people in the traitor generation! Um \'85
 (LAUGHS) Crazy idea! Yes, Frank had been at Cambridge when I was at LSE in Cambridge, and his parents were also Christian Scientists, by reason of which we washed up in the same lodging house. And my friend, Mary, and I, had a double room at the back of 
one of those big houses in the road that comes down from the station \endash  Salisbury Crescent, I think, or something \endash  and Frank had the room in the front. I didn\rquote 
t really see him very much because - here we go again! - the men were given meals in a dining room by themselves, and the women dined with the family. You couldn\rquote t get away from these things. If it wasn\rquote t class, it was gender \endash 
 not that we called it that then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 What did you call it then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Sex, I think. I think so. Yes. Anyway, so Mary and I 
got to know him, and Mary said she thought he was lonely. So we used to have him in to have dried eggs scrambled on toast, or something very exotic. The landlord and landlady didn\rquote 
t know about this at all, they would have been incredibly shocked! So that was just how I got to know him. And then he went off to the War. He was called up as a bi-termer, I think, one January, and he came home on one of those week\rquote 
s leaves that they called \'93Monty\rquote s Leaves\'94 - after the War was over, they could come back every six months for a week. So, one week, we decided that we would get married, and we got married, I think, in the following \'85
 ah hah! I remember what it was now! He\rquote d come over for these seven days, okay? So we spent the seven days. Then there were the most ghas
tly storms in the Channel, so everybody was left on leave longer, until the storms passed, so that they could be safely transported back to France, or wherever they were, and so in those three days, we decided, \'93
Well, we might as well get married and then we could have the next leave entirely to ourselves\'94. So I think that\rquote 
s what we did. And we got a bishop to give us a licence. Neither of us were Anglican, but the Register Office was shut, and would do nothing on a weekend. Anyway, so we got married. And then we had the next \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 You got married very quickly, in fact, having decided.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Having decided, yes. Yes, that\rquote s right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And who came to the wedding? 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 My parents. His mother \endash  his father had already died. Just a handful of people, you
 know, sort of a few friends that were about. But I\rquote d never wanted a big fussy wedding, so it suited me all right. I exploited the situation to get away! We were married from my mother-in-law\rquote 
s house, because that was where we could get the Bishop to give us the licence. I must have been staying there. I must have been staying there at the time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And then he went back to the Forces?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 He went back to the Forces, and then he was moved to Palestine, and he was part of the Army, the \'93
Occupation Forces\'94 that has been referred to so much in the last months, part of the dreaded British oppression. And then he finally, I suppose, got demobbed about \rquote 47. And I\rquote d been living and working in Banbury all of this time, that
\rquote s where I was when I got married, and
 we got half a house to live in. And then we got a whole house - because at that time, all private building, there was a big moratorium on it, there was only public building, unless you had a place which had been started before the War and the development
 
had been stopped because of the War. And there was one such [house] down in Grimsbury, on the East side of Banbury, and we managed to get the money together to buy one of those. It cost the whole of a thousand pounds. Little tiny box, basic utility, you k
now. So that was where we lived until Frank got a job in Wales.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 In Swansea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
In Swansea. And in the meantime, having finished his degree in Cambridge, he then went and did an M.Phil. in Oxford. It was when he\rquote d finished the M.Phil. that we then went down to Wales.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 So what was his subject?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Political Studies. Don\rquote t call it Political Science, please, he wouldn\rquote 
t have given you a thank you to that!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 (LAUGHS) Yes! And then you had children fairly soon, or \'85
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
No, not fairly soon. In fact, we were diagnosed as infertile, or I was, or he was, or as a couple we were. And so we adopted two children, a boy and then a girl. Then suddenly, I fell pregnant. In fact, funnily enough, Peter, my third child, must have bee
n conceived at roughly the time that Kate, my second child, was born. There was about ten months between them. So I had quite a handful with these two little ones, in the sense in which if you have one that\rquote s very close to another, they\rquote 
re harder to manage than twins, because one has greater physical strength and mobility and things. Then, after three years, I had another child. So that there were two we adopted, and two I bore. And then, that was a {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK1}
{\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK2}quiverful! {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK1}{\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK2}
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 I\rquote d always
 meant to have four kids, and that was quite enough for me, because being one of two I hadn\rquote 
t found comfortable. And then there was an SOS went round the Senior Common Room for a home for a black girl whose foster home had broken down, and we had a family 
conference about it, and everybody thought we should take her in. She was 13, nearly 14, and of an Irish mother and a Ghanaian father, insofar as I know, and she\rquote 
d been in this foster home since she was three or four, her father had died. She was very inte
lligent, by far the most intelligent of the family, and they thought that that was creating [some of] her problems. She had manifold problems, understandably. She\rquote d been taken in to replace a child they\rquote 
d lost, and she was brought into an all white neighbourhood. The only black people she ever saw were down in Cardiff Docks. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 So this was in the sixties?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
Mm-mm. And so she came to us, and she was older than all our children, which was not something one was supposed to do. But in any case, there she was, and she\rquote s really, really bright, and she\rquote s done very well.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 What\rquote s happened to the children, in fact?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Well, if I start with Pat, because she\rquote s the oldest. She\rquote 
s currently working as a judge on asylum appeals, which was a job she was tra
ined for in Canada, where she was living until recently. She, before that, had worked for Coopers Lybrand, which was where she met her present husband. She read architecture at Liverpool, and then interior design at the Universit\'e9 de Montr\'e9
al in Canada. She did that for a while, doing urban design, and then it didn\rquote 
t work out. She had lots and lots of jobs, but, in any case, she gave it up and went to work, using her skills, for Coopers Lybrand. And then, for whatever reason, the Federal Government of Canad
a were advertising for people to help sort out the asylum seekers, and she got a job there. And she\rquote s now having a very rough time, being a judge, being a woman and black, and not a lawyer, which most of them are lawyers. She finds that that
\rquote s heavy on one side, as the actual cases are quite heavy. And the rest of us are afraid that she\rquote s getting more and more reactionary in consequence of these experiences! (LAUGHS) But I hope this isn\rquote t true. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Then Richard, Richard went to Sussex, did psychology, didn\rquote t 
enjoy it, went to work in the City, and cutting a long story short, made money, lost money, and now he\rquote s living as a farmer in an uneconomic farm in the Black Mountains. We\rquote 
ve got four grandchildren by that marriage, he had two by an earlier marriage. Jennifer always says, \'93These are the happiest of all my grandchildren\'94, and yet they\rquote re the poorest, by a long chalk. So that\rquote 
s what Richard is doing, and his wife is doing all sorts of craft things to help supplement their income. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
