\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 So how did you manage it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
Well, for starters, I never set out to have a professional career. I was just interested in doing sociology, which had opened my eyes enormously. I mean, this I didn\rquote t mention when we were talking about LSE, but what I can remember was Ginsberg
\rquote s lectures too. Suddenly, all sorts of things in my experience of being my grandmother\rquote s granddaughter, and being my mother\rquote s daughter, and my father\rquote 
s daughter, and going to the school I went to, and all those things, and what I\rquote d seen
 about the world, went click, click, click in [my head]. Although Ginsberg is pretty theoretical, philosophical, and then other things that I had too, I mean other lectures too, of course, also had an influence. But I really wanted to do sociology, so 
\'85 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
So the question really is, how did you manage to do the sociology and be a professional as well as bringing up the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 That\rquote s right, and I was saying I didn\rquote t have a career. I didn\rquote t have a career. I\rquote 
d been teaching in Oxford, and partly for the Oxford Social Training Delegacy as well. Then I went to Wales and John Fulton, who\rquote d been my employer in Oxford, was Principal of the College, and told the Council, when Frank was appointed, \'93
And in getting Mr. Stacey, we have Mrs. Stacey, who\rquote s an academic in her own right.\'94
 And nobody gave me a job for ten years! But ultimately, when the sociology explosion occurred in the sixties, they finally scraped the bottom of the barrel and found they were appointing young men who never came to the job beca
use they got a better job in England, so they scraped the bottom of the barrel and, lo and behold, there was me, whom they would refuse to employ because I was married with children. And so that was how I got the job. And this is really relevant, because 
\'85
