\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 This is the Swansea job.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 So from 1951 to 1961, you didn\rquote t have a job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Something like that, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Though you were teaching off and on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 No, I wasn\rquote t teaching. I was really \'85
 It was really extraordinary, because the WEA, which was very strong, wouldn\rquote t have me, because I was a married woman. I mean, the Welsh were like that \endash  I trust they\rquote 
ve changed! And the person, Robert Hughes-Jones, [who] ran the Social Work/Social Science Department, and that was the only place I could have applied for a job initially. He wouldn\rquote 
t have me because I was a married woman with children, which, I believe, was not unconnected with the fact that his wife had a first from Somerville and was at home with the children all the time. I don\rquote 
t know what the connection there was. So, and because we\rquote d had the experience of the War, of long years of not living together, I really didn\rquote t want to apply to Bristol, for example, for a job, which would have been
 about the [nearest] - Cardiff or Bristol, and probably more likely Bristol. You know, I just didn\rquote 
t want to risk messing up the family. I refused to apply for a job in Swansea, as a professor, that must have been in the Social Work Department, and that was partly because I just didn\rquote 
t think it would be very good for the marriage. This sounds very anti-Feminist, but I just wanted to keep that going. And so I wasn\rquote t thinking of a career, but I was wanting to teach sociology, so that\rquote s what I did. I obviously
 needed help on the domestic front with the kids. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
The first job I had was working for the Lower Swansea Valley Project as a researcher, and they wanted me to work part-time, and I did for a while. And I said, \'93I\rquote m sorry, I cannot afford working part-time, because I\rquote 
ve got these kids, and I must replace my domestic work at home\'94. So they gave me a full-time job in the end, but it took me a long time to persuade them \endash  \'93them\'94 all being men, needless to say! So I refused that. So, in a way, I didn
\rquote t break out, like young women, nowadays, I think, do, but I knew what I was about. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
And then finally, suddenly, Frank applied for, and got, a Chair at Nottingham, and so then I felt free to apply for a Chair, and I was \'85
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 It was about how Frank got the offer in Nottingham.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Oh yes, that\rquote 
s right. I know what I was going to say. I was going to say how his boss thought, because I was going to stay in Swansea while he started his job in Nottingham, that our marriage was breaking up. And this was generally thought. So we said, \'93No\'94 \'85
 Well, I\rquote ll just say that people thought that we were breaking up, because I said I\rquote d stay in Swansea till I could get another job, and Frank was going off to Nottingham. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 But I just thought, I had been "unemployed", quote/unquote,
 for ten years, and I didn\rquote t want back into that situation, so I wasn\rquote t going to go until I\rquote 
d got a job. So I then applied for whatever Chairs there were. Because that was obviously - I mean, I was a Senior Lecturer by now, and Director of the Medical Soci
ology Research Unit, and that was clearly what I should go for. And Keith Kelsall wanted me to go to Sheffield, and John Rex wanted me in Warwick, and I decided for Warwick, basically because Sheffield, then, was much too much like Swansea had been, with 
male domination and all of that, and I thought, \'93I cannot go through that again! I\rquote ve just come out the other side of it!\'94 And so that was how I came to go to Warwick. And then, of course, John Rex found that I was impossible! He\rquote 
s brilliant at picking good people, John Rex, and hopeless at living with them! Fascinating! But, in any case, he wanted me and he got me \endash  for better or for worse! (LAUGHS) 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 So then you, you moved to Warwick, and Frank had another place in Nottingham then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 No, we got a place in Husband\rquote 
s Bosworth in South Leicestershire, and he went up the M1, and I came across country, there is a motorway connection now, but there wasn\rquote t then. And so that was fine, except that he died very soon. He wasn\rquote t - I never thought he was reall
y happy in the new job. But he\rquote 
d had some problems - well, I was always worried about his blood pressure and things like that, when he was in Swansea. And he had two attacks of thrombosis, one which was spontaneous, and one which was induced by a surgeon t
rying to find out what sort of thrombosis he had, so he got another one in the site of what they said was the cause of it. And it turns out that the village GP didn\rquote 
t do a good enough job, and he died of hypertensive heart failure, which nobody should have done. That was \rquote 77. \rquote 77, and we came up in \rquote 74. So that wasn\rquote t very long.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 No. And you were on your own for quite a long time after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Well, yes. Kate was living in the house in a little flatlet we\rquote d made, with her baby, when Frank died. He
 was 54. But she had just got a Council flat in Lutterworth allocated, and so she said, \'93Mum, I\rquote m sorry, I\rquote ve got to go\'94. So I said, \'93Well, of course you\rquote ve got to go\'94. I mean, it\rquote 
s the first piece of decent living accommodation she\rquote d had. And it was the s
ame, the same weekend Frank died, was the weekend that my youngest son went up to university, so they all fled the nest at once. And I went on living there. But then Kate had had a second child who had severe cerebral palsy and was being cared for by the 
Church of England Children\rquote s Society, as it were, in exchange for our having taken Pat on board, that was how we got the connection. She had this child, that\rquote s right, and the Church of England Children\rquote 
s Society finally decided that she was too severely handicapped for them to look after any longer, and she was to go back to the Health Service. And I knew, I didn\rquote t have to go and see them, because I knew because of the work I\rquote 
d done in Wales, in hospitals, exactly how bad the hospitals that the child might have been sent to, were, and found, through a paediatrician that I\rquote 
d been working with, doing research with, that there was a new Unit setting up not far from here, in Weston-under-Weatherly, and that was all right. The doctor said, \'93Come, bring the child\'94. The nurses hadn\rquote 
t been consulted, the doctors forgot to consult them, and the nurses, for some reason, didn\rquote t think they wanted a grandchild of mine - they thought I would make trouble, surprise, surprise! And so they vetoed it on the grounds that I didn\rquote 
t live in the County. It\rquote s a very Elizabeth I kind of Poor Law. So with indecent haste, I moved and got a house here [in Leamington]. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
So then I was living alone in Lansdowne Circus for quite a while, and then I suppose it was about 1982, Jennifer and I took up together, so after a while she came and lived in my house, and she\rquote s got a house in Derbyshire, and I live there too. 

\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And what did you say she does, actually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 She\rquote s an Italianist.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 She teaches Italian?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 No, she\rquote s retired. She\rquote s taken an early retirement, and she\rquote s an expert on Pirandello. She
\rquote s just finishing a book for Cambridge on productions of Pirandello\rquote s plays. She did the Department a great service by leaving. It was a great gamble, because it was too small, the Italian Department, and it had never had a professor 
\endash  she was a Senior Lecturer \endash  and she took a gamble because they really might have closed the Department, or used her [post] to do something [else]. Fortunately, they saw the light. I think Bob Bu
rgess may have been not uninfluential in helping them to see the light. So they\rquote ve now appointed a professor and some further staff, and the Department is much better than it was before. And she\rquote 
s glad to be out, because it had been a millstone. It isn\rquote t that she doesn\rquote t like doing Italian, but the Department had a weak Head. Weak Heads are always a pain.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
Just one last thing about your marriage, was there an intellectual exchange going on there in the marriage, or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Yes. Yes. Yes, I think so
. We had a lot of interests in common. We also had divergences, which made for interest. Frank\rquote 
s particular expertise was in the Ombudsman in the early days of the Ombudsman. So we had a lot of common interest in things to do with the regulation of public 
bodies and so on, and where we differed was that I was more radical than he was. You know, he was a one for change when it was necessary, but he wasn\rquote t a radical really, and I tended to be a bit wild, I suppose! (LAUGHS) Well, not always orthodox.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And you did say just now, or you rather implied that you think you\rquote 
re difficult to get on with. Do you really think that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Oh no, I don\rquote t think I am difficult to get on with, I think John Rex is! (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 \tab Oh, you think it\rquote s him! (LAUGHS)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 (LAUGHS) Well, it was just this pattern, it didn\rquote t matter at what grade he appointed anybody, but \'85
 you\rquote d better switch the thing off! 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 [BREAK IN RECORDING]
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 So how did you get the idea of doing the first Banbury Study?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 It was as follows. As I
 mentioned, I was working in Banbury for the Extra-Mural Delegacy of Oxford, and associated with that I had a class, three-year class, for aluminium factory workers, and any others in Banbury who wanted to come, but it was arranged for the aluminium worke
rs. And I was pretty isolated in this job. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 There was no sociology at all in Oxford 
at the time. I think John Logie had already gone in despair, and so the nearest thing was anthropology. So I muscled my way into the anthropology seminars, and Evans-Pritchard and Meyer Fortes were there at that time. Of course, learning under Ginsberg, w
e got a lot of anthropology in the course of doing that, so I wasn\rquote t unfamiliar with that approach. And Meyer Fortes, one day, said to me \endash 
 rather curiously, in view of that whole business about you have to go and do your research work abroad, in another language, that they were quite religious about at one time \endash  he said, \'93
Will you mind if I come, one day, to Banbury, to do a study of Banbury?\'94 So I said, \'93No\'94. And I sort of went on working there, and I hung about, and no sign of Meyer Fortes. So I went to see him, one day, and I said, \'93
Meyer, do you remember that you thought of doing a study in Banbury?\'94 And he sort of mumbled, so I said, \'93Well, would you mind if I did one? And I\rquote ve got this class, and they\rquote ve already done some groundwork and \'85 dah-di-dah\'94.
 And he didn\rquote t seem to mind, he thought that was all right. So that was how it started. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
It started with no money at all. I mean, it was me and the class, extending that work. And then Charles Kimber came to join in, and he had money of his own, so he didn\rquote t necessarily need a salary.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 So where was he based, then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 He had read history, I think, at Oxford, and he hadn\rquote 
t got a good degree at all, but he was very interested, and I must have met him in the anthropology seminars.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 So when you say he didn\rquote t need money, he had some teaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
No. I think he was a scion of the upper class, of a sort. That is to say his father was a baronet, and I think they had money. I don\rquote t think they had masses, I mean, he did work when he could, but he seemed to be able to live without \'85
 You know, you and I would have needed a weekly salary, monthly salary or whatever. Anyway, so [we] finally got \'a32,000 or something \endash  that was a great sum in those days \endash  from the Nuffield Foundation. With that, we were able
 to employ some helpers, plus Cyril Smith came to work with us, so there were three of us, and people who helped with interviewing. Things like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Cyril Smith, is that the future MP?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 No, the future Secretary of the SSRC, before it was the ESRC. He was somebody who\rquote 
d benefited from being in the Army, because he was able to get to university, which he otherwise wouldn\rquote t have been able to. He came out of a quite poor working-class family in South London. So we had an interesting class spread, b
ecause I was out of the suburbs, and there was this Old Etonian, and then Cyril. That was quite interesting. So that was how that arose. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
It was all linked with the ideas that I had that we needed empirical data about ordinary populations, as I mentioned earlier, not just problem cases. So that was what I set out to do. I suppose I took }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Middletown}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768  and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Middletown in Transition}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768  as models of a kind. I was also influenced by what I called the \'93social accountability\'94 kind of data, you know, the work that I\rquote d do
ne for my Social Science non-Certificate - because if you did the work, you didn\rquote 
t get the Certificate during the War! I mentioned both of those things, I think, in the introduction. And that was enough for Michael Banton to say that was when he parted com
pany with it, Banbury was no good because it had these sullied influences from people who did good works. I don\rquote t know what Michael\rquote s objections were!
