\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
The problems? Well an important lot of problems came around Ann, because the blokes complained to me that she wasn\rquote t working and so on, and she complained that they weren\rquote t being nice to her. And she wasn\rquote t in the office. Th
ey were often in the office, I think they were in the office too much. I don\rquote t know. But she wasn\rquote t being paid to be in the office, she was being paid to interact with the women, and you can\rquote 
t be at the school gate meeting your kids and talking to the other mums if you\rquote re in the office \endash  if you understand what I mean! So there was some problem there. And the work that she did, I thought was good. I mean, that stuff on \'93
One-End Street\'94, the interactions in that cul-de-sac, it\rquote s the sort of thing that you might expect a female anthropologist to be able to do, after all. I thought she did it well, and as far as I could see, she was joining in. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
Colin turned out not to be a good team leader. He was a good, brilliant fieldworker, as I say, but he wasn\rquote t a good team leader, and that was a very great shame. And I also discovered that he\rquote 
d been doing what I thought was quite inappropriate. There was a big Election, General Election, around the time, and instead of interviewing people to find out what they thought, e
vidence reached me that he was persuading people to vote Labour, and I just thought that was wrong. I mean, he\rquote d chosen to work with the Labour Party side of the political spectrum, well, that was all right, but \'85
 I did read him a long lecture about not imposing upon people\rquote s views, and trying to change their views. That made me very worried, it made me very worried, I felt there was a sort of exploitation, it was a sort of lack of honesty. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 So that turned out, that study, to be far less - although it was 
richly endowed, turned out to be, I think, far less satisfactory than the other one. And when Colin finally walked out, which he did - I mean, he just walked out, and in the course of doing so, punched Eric on the nose. I mean - (LAUGHS) - I found it very
 difficult, and I\rquote ve never really - I\rquote ve never made a reply to any of that stuff that he came up with. And I\rquote m quite sure I made a load of mistakes and I\rquote 
m very happy to say that. But I think he behaved pretty badly. So those, I think, were the problems. Eric, in the meanwhile, was beavering away on what he was doing, which was trying to make sense of the Conservative \endash  big C and little c \endash 
 part of the town, and understand about the economics and things like that. It\rquote s very strange, and it made me conclude that, really, replication isn\rquote t possible.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Ah! Now why do you think that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 In any tidy sort of way. I\rquote d always resisted the idea, which I read in various places, that you couldn
\rquote t do these things because personalities were so much involved, or individuality if not personality. But I really began to feel that that might be so. The idea of having Ann as a young mother, as she then was when I appointed her, because she
\rquote d started bearing children when she was an undergraduate I think, was that she was at a different stage of the changes in women\rquote s lives from what I\rquote 
d been at. I was a married woman without children, working, and that was bad enough (because I didn\rquote t adopt Richard until after we\rquote d left Banbury) and she 
was a married women with children, working. And that, in the ways the arguments went, in those days, put her in a different but comparable slot, to the one that I\rquote d been in. I don\rquote t think that match really quite worked. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And did you still believe in the basic concepts about tradition and change?
