t bear it. They hated it, and they kept telling me so. And I think it was partly simply that the town had spread and encroached the fields, so that whereas I was able to get out into the country if that\rquote s what I wanted to do, they couldn\rquote 
t. Yet it lacked urban amenities for people who liked city
 dwelling. And that was a change, because it was essentially a market town, and it was a vibrant and interesting market town, with all this new industry going on, and a certain amount of tension about the place, and I really enjoyed being there, and I lik
ed the people I met. I don\rquote t know whether the second team ever made any friends in Banbury, real friends, as it were. So, yes, I mean, I liked living there. And it was still okay when they did the second survey, but mind you, I wasn\rquote 
t ever very long. But I went down a couple of times before doing this interview with Laurie, and I ought to go back and investigate it more deeply!
