\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
The original studies were done with children in long-stay care, and it struck me that there were a lot of social, sociological problems, that weren\rquote 
t addressed at all, like the fact that the nurses had gone on revolt about having unrestricted visiting for mothers. Because it\rquote s not surprising, it totally altered their working space, it totally messed up their practices, and one of the thin
gs we found when we talked to them was, \'93Well, since the mothers came in, there\rquote s always mess\'94. And you\rquote 
d look round the ward, and the mothers had put their bags quite neatly under a chair or something, and the mess was symbolic to their lives being messed
 up. And there was no backstage left for them, except really in the sluice or somewhere. There was also no discussion [in Bowlby's work or in] James Robertson\rquote s either, and what it did to the families that the sick child had come from \endash 
 the siblings and the parents and how did they manage, and all of that, and none of that was looked at. So it seemed to me that there was a case for some sociological research to be done here. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 So I thought it\rquote 
s about time I did some [more] research, [this] was the sort of thing I ought to be doing. And so I didn\rquote t know which way round this mountain, there was no health research really funded then. So I talked to my GP, who was an old friend by now 
\endash  if you\rquote ve got four or five children, you get to know your GP very well, as you probably know! And I said, \'93Look, if I did this, who do I go to?\'94
 So he referred me to the person he knew in what was then the Ministry of Health, and I talked to that person, who then said, \'93Well, look, we\rquote ve just started getting some money for research, and the persons you want to see are X, Y and Z\'94
. And I did, and I wrote a proposal, and got some research money to do the first study.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Who was that from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 It was from the Ministry. It was these new research funds that were being released. It was when they\rquote 
d really realised that they should do it. And I was supervised in the Civil Service way, by Marjorie Simpson who, herself, was a nurse, and she was the research nurse person, and she was really lovely, and a tower of strength. And so it was 
seen by the Ministry as in a sense, a nursing project, at least that was where it got pigeonholed. So they produced the money. And who did we have working on that? A psychiatrist, me, and an anthropologist. I think we didn\rquote 
t have the psychologist until the
 second time. I get confused without looking it up. So we were looking for things like, were children damaged by being put into hospital, separated from their families? And if so, which ones? And could this separation effect be found in children in acute 
stay, or is it only in children in long-stay? So that was all very interesting. Nobody very much believed the results.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Now, what were the methods this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 The methods were observation, so that people were sitting in wards, watching what happe
ned. There was some numerate analysis which, interestingly enough, was instituted by the anthropologist, who was the daughter of a doctor, and said, \'93If we don\rquote t have some figures in this, nobody\rquote s going to believe it\'94
. But she, herself, I think, felt insecure without some numerate frame. So it was observation and interviews with the staff, and observation of the children. We hadn\rquote 
t got to the learning that has been achieved by people working with children now, like Priscilla Alderson, for example, and Alan Prout who realised that you could interview quite young children. I think most of ours weren\rquote 
t - well, anyway, I think we were objectifying the children, probably. The awful things one\rquote s done in one\rquote s life! Terrible! (LAUGHS) So I think that was really it
. I think that was really it. So there was a certain amount of counting of what was happening to children in their time. We were able to say the extent to which children were unoccupied and alone, without just saying as an impression. I think we had some 
figures attached to it, and I think that was what Roisin Pill instituted. So I think that was about it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And didn\rquote t you say there were two children in hospital studies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Yes. Then we did some more later. One of the ways in which the professions h
ad tried to write off this research was by saying, \'93Oh, it was in Wales. Things are like that in Wales\'94. So we got money to do some studies in England, and this is the book that\rquote s published as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Beyond Separation,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768  by Hall and Stacey, which should be down there, as brackets with Hall, but may not be there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Yes. That\rquote s 1979, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And the interesting thing that came out of that was that, struggle as we might, we couldn\rquote 
t get a common conceptual framework. You can see that if you look at the book, and that the psychologist is the psychologist - it wasn\rquote t that we didn\rquote t try to, but we had to really leave it. There\rquote 
s a number of relatively discrete bits. We had a psychologist the second time round, rather than a psychiatrist. She\rquote d been a disaster in the first study.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Yes. In what sense a disaster?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
She, like many practitioners, really found it very difficult to get into a research mode, and be detached and things like that. I\rquote 
d met her, initially, because she was one of the [people who were] agitating, on the Bowlby lines, about how terrible it was to separate children from their mothers, which she got from her psychiatric training. But this is why the second time
, we had a psychologist \endash 
 at least one could see what he was doing in terms of research. It was he, and I refer to this in the conclusion of the book that was recently published by my colleagues in Warwick, bless their little cotton socks, which was done as a sort of }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 festschrift }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
for me, they asked me to write the concluding comments, and I referred, there, to how I was concerned about what was important in the research, was to point out that, in terms of trying to heal the children, unnecessary and unintend
ed suffering was inflicted, and the psychologist didn\rquote t want me to leave that word \'93suffering\'94 in. I think he thought it was emotive, or would be seen as unscientific. I don\rquote t know what it was, but I left it there. And I\rquote 
m not sorry I did, because that was
 what it was really about. There are things that you can measure, whether you see children crying or not crying, stuff like that. But in any case, I thought that was rather nice to see that after all those years, because I can remember, I really had to sa
y to myself, in the end, \'93Well, you\rquote re the boss here, and you want that word there, it says what you mean. Put it in\'94.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
Okay. Shall we do the last bit of research? The General Medical Council. Shall we go straight on, or have a break?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\ul\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Well, let\rquote s have a break long enough for me to make a cup of tea!
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 [BREAK IN RECORDING]
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 So, let\rquote s talk about the last major bit of empirical work, which was about the \'85
 General Medical Council.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Right. Well, as I say in the beginning of that book, or its Introduction or somewhere, I didn\rquote 
t accept appointment to the GMC for research purposes. I did it as a public service, in the way that I had served on the Hospital Board, and the Hospital Management Committee, the Welsh Hospital Board and things like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 So let\rquote 
s just take that back, though. So you got on to the Welsh Hospital Board when you were in Swansea, some time in the sixties would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 \tab Yes. It was a result of the activities of the Association for the Welfare of Children in Hospit
al, of which I was one of the founder members, plus the research that followed that was funded from the Ministry, as I was explaining to you, and thus my name got known. And I also had been introduced to - oh gosh! Sorry, her name has gone! - who was Mini
ster of Health at the time. She was a great redoubtable Welsh Labour woman. She was a friend. Do you remember I said there was a woman who said, \'93Release this woman\'94
 on some papers of mine? And they were friends. So she was told about me. And she wanted me to be a JP, constantly.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And you became a JP, or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
No. I - I refused, because I knew that the bench was, in Swansea, was not a good bench, and it would have been impossible, if one was there, not to get involved in trying to improve it. And 
I was very busy at work, and I was busy with children, so I said no. It\rquote s turned out to be a terrible thing to do, because it\rquote 
s like turning down some sort of honour. But as far as I was concerned, it was a job of work, and one would have to be concerned to see that justice was done \endash  as far as that\rquote 
s ever possible. So I said no to that. And then after some time, she came back to me, and she said, \'93Well \'85\'94 would I do these other things? So I was, first of all, put on a Hospital Management Committee, and fro
m there I was translated to the Welsh Hospital Board, and I served on that under Gwillam Rees-Davies. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 I think it was from there \endash 
 they never tell you how you get on to the GMC, it\rquote s one of these nasty British secrets! I know that all the Regional Boards 
will have been asked for nominations, and I think that Gwillam Rees-Davies will have - and I also get this from letters he wrote to me about, would I be interested in blah-di-blah? He wrote and said that I was an appropriate person to serve on the GMC and
 among his private reasons was the fact that he wanted somebody who, if not Welsh, could speak for Wales, should that kind of an issue come up. So that was how I got there. And I accepted because I\rquote 
d been involved in all sorts of issues to do with hospital complaints. I hadn\rquote 
t studied the professions in a formalistic way, like plenty of people had done. I just read it tangentially, on the surface. So there I was, a lay member of the GMC. But I decided, right from the beginning, that I ought to keep notes and
 stuff, because it seemed to be very important that we should understand about it. So I did this. And I served from \rquote 76 to \rquote 83, some such dates.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Have you kept those notes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 I think so. I think they\rquote re in the records. And what I think I\rquote 
ve put in is all the agendas and minutes and stuff, with annotations round the edges. I know the doctors all said that I was spying on them, when they saw me scribbling away! And I said, \'93No, no, I\rquote ve got to keep awake!\'94
 (LAUGHS) And really, it was monumentally boring, quite often, so they understood that. And I was on various Committees, like the Health Committee, and the Conduct Committee, and learnt \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 How did the idea of the study come?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Well, I thought, from the beginning, that it would be inappropriate if I didn\rquote 
t use this and make it available. It seemed to me that sociologists had all been scrabbling around and researching the poor, but not very often researching the wealthy and the powerful and so on. Whereas the GMC is not a powerful arm of government, it
\rquote s on the edges of government, and there are moments when it can be quite powerful. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
It was very interesting. I was one of three women. One of the other two were lay. The rest were all men. There were 43 people on the Council at that time. And there were various upheavals in the medical profession going on, and that\rquote 
s always interesting, because it\rquote s like when the norms are raised, you get a better idea of what\rquote s going on. And then there were various other things. But I think I must have opened my mouth once too many, because I wasn\rquote 
t reappointed in \rquote 83. I was quite surprised to have been reappointed in \rquote 79, because I think perhaps Thatcher had already just got there, and hadn\rquote t realised who her enemies were or something! I don\rquote t know whether that\rquote 
s what it was, but, in any case, they never tell you. They send you an appointment paper letter, on a very thick piece of paper, and when they dismiss you, they send it on a very thin piece of paper! Quite amusing! In any case, so usually people d
id three terms, and I only did two. So after that, I thought, \'93Well, now, the time has come \'85\'94
, so I looked for some money to back it up. I decided that I would do it by myself, but I would need, as it were, secretarial/administrative help. So I had all th
at data from participant observation of formal Council Meetings, and the Committees that I was appointed to, and then when I got going on the research, and I did everything by the book, completely above-board, you know, told them what I was doing, got the
ir support, promised them that I would let them see everything I was going to publish, before it came out, and all of those things, so I then interviewed all the senior members of the Council. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 I didn\rquote 
t actually do the bureaucracy, I focused really on the Council. That would be another study to - and a very interesting one which would be quite nice to do, if one had one\rquote s youth and energy \endash 
 the relationship between the bureaucracy and the politicos. So I met these doctors for lunch, in various places, and \'85
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And you found that interviewing over lunch was the best technique, then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Well, that was when you could get hold of them. And I could hear in a restaurant then. I can\rquote 
t hear mostly in restaurants now, because of the cacophony around about, and my ears just \'85 Open space is nice, and the whole of that restaurant that we were at today, it doesn\rquote t have terribly high decibels, especially if you\rquote 
re out in the air, so I couldn\rquote 
t use that technique now, but I did then, and it worked quite well. And not everybody did I interview like that, but there were some people that that was the way to catch them. There were others that it was easier to meet in the Royal Society of Medicine,
 for example, of which I\rquote m a Fellow. So they were interviews where you could find people, and I just - I didn\rquote 
t have a formal schedule at all, I just was interested in hearing what they had to say. There were obviously questions in my head that I would put in, but it wasn\rquote t formalised. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 \tab What\rquote 
s the difference, in your experience, between interviewing an elite like these people and, say, interviewing the people in the Lower Swansea Valley?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Access, I think, is one thing. I mean, people in the Lower Swansea Valley, or anywhere else, don\rquote 
t need to open the door, or they can slam it. On the other hand, they\rquote re mostly open and helpful \endash  or they were in my day! Perhaps they all work too hard now, I don\rquote t know. Whereas elite people, I think they\rquote re quite
 as happy to talk about themselves, as most people are, or to have an opportunity to express their opinions \endash  also as most people are, I think \endash  but they\rquote re just awfully cagey, because they\rquote 
re involved in high politics of one sort or another, inevitably, by the nature of who they are and where they are \endash  may not be on the scene you\rquote re interested in, but in connected scenes - so they tend to be cagey.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And does that also mean it\rquote s more difficult handling them, too, after you\rquote 
ve done the interview? For instance, you said that the GMC wanted to look at what you wrote, but did you also have to clear each quotation with the people you interviewed, or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 No. I don\rquote t think I promised them to do that. I don\rquote t know how much I used direct quotations, bec
ause the book, itself, is concerned with the history of the GMC, its structure, its organisation in some ways, and I was writing it, not for sociologists, but for doctors, because I was wanting to say to them, \'93Look, you\rquote 
re going to be in dead trouble if you don\rquote t mend your ways\'94. And I, therefore, didn\rquote 
t write it as a sociological book. In fact I got a terrible review from Robert Dingwell, who told me all the stuff about the professions, that I ought to have quoted. It was horrible. But I wasn\rquote t meaning to
 do that, I was wanting to make it accessible to anybody who wanted to read it. But I wanted to talk to the doctors and tell them what I\rquote 
d seen, and what effects it was having, and did they understand? Donald Irvine, who was then President, had always seen me as an ally on the Council, I think, and he picked it up. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 In the end of the book I went throug
h all this stuff about the dispute about whether self-regulation is a good idea, or whether you should have regulation by external authority. I decided, basically, that self-regulation is appropriate, as long as it works, as long as it isn\rquote 
t just an Old Boys\rquote  Club patting each other on the back, and told them that they needed a new sort of professionalism. And it sold a lot of copies \endash  for a book like that [several thousand]. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 So that was 1992, I think, wasn\rquote t it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Something like that. It took m
e forever to do. It was very difficult. It threw me into a depression, I decided, after a while.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 What was so difficult, then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
It was all the tensions. (LAUGHS) I once went down to wherever that place is on the South Coast, the publishers, to see the editor, which I hadn\rquote 
t done before, and told her that I really was very worried about the progress of the book, and I must have only articulated at that time, I said that, \'93Sometimes, I feel as if I\rquote ve got half a dozen of these old fogies stood behind me\'94
, and it was as if they were holding my hand or my fingers or something, saying, \'93You can\rquote t say that\'94. I mean, this was completely in imagining, but it was a way of trying to express what I was feeling. And she said, \'93Well, you don\rquote 
t need to worry. We get a lot of young doctors with completely different ideas, coming in here\'94
. That really was very nice, because whenever I got these ghostly old men as it were, looking over my shoulder, I imagined all these young new doctors coming in with smiling faces! I mean, I wasn\rquote 
t doing that all the time, but it was just an important turning point. And it was actually deciding what one ought to say, (a) in terms of what was the truth of the matter, insofar as the truth is ever anything that one can get a hold of, 
and (b) in what it would be acceptable to write \endash  not that people would approve of, but just that one could get away with, if you like.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And did they take notice of it, do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Well, I mean, they immediately, after it came out, ran into t
he Bristol trouble and the Alderhay trouble and the Shipman trouble, so they had plenty of troubles. And the thing I had been saying was, \'93You don\rquote t know what you\rquote re doing, and what the resentment is\'94
. I suppose something that added up to that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Fine. So, I think that\rquote s about it on the research, unless there\rquote 
s anything else that you can think of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 No, I don\rquote t think so. I can\rquote 
t, at this moment, quite recall all the processes I went through, in disentangling the data, and deciding what to make of it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 \tab Well, if more thoughts come to you, I mean, we can always write them in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 \tab Okay. Okay.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
Can I just ask, now, about two moments when there are new influences coming in? And one you have mentioned a little bit, about the second wave of Feminism. How far do you think that changed the way you did things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 I think it changed it quite a lot, in the sense that words for concepts became available, which one couldn
\rquote t appropriately articulate before, because the words weren\rquote t there. So that made it much more possible to handle what one was trying to [say]. Certainly it also directed my mind, to areas that I hadn\rquote 
t really addressed before. And when all the business about assisted childbirth, assisted conception and birth, and then about genetic
 engineering, came along, it made it possible for me to get allies. At that time, I was on the WHO, Medical Research Advisory Committee in Copenhagen, and I was trying to persuade them to open up the area of the social research in relation to genetics, as
 well as the physiological and clinical and stuff like that. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
And the way that the second wave Feminism mattered, was that I was readily able to get hold of a bunch of young w
omen who were willing to come to a seminar to discuss how I should present this. I wrote this paper with the help of these seven or eight women. I wouldn\rquote 
t have even known where to look for women like that, formerly. So that was really important, the fact 
that the women, themselves, had got together and articulated the ideas, and they were very happy to do it, because it was a voice in a place that there wasn\rquote 
t one before. I remember Marilyn Strathern was most impressed, who came and did work in this area afterwards, that I\rquote d, in fact, as early as I did, brought it up. Mind you, we got absolutely nowhere, but at least we tried.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And then were you influenced at all by post-Modernism?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Not really. I think post-Modernism flooded on the market so much towards the end of my career, that I didn
\rquote t really - I mean, I had my head stuck down in the GMC, and I was doing that according to a model I\rquote d had before, and I wasn\rquote t bothering with anything. What I did read about post-Modernism didn\rquote t impress me. So, no, I don
\rquote t think I was affected by that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Now, then there\rquote 
s another important area of activity to do with the BSA. Could you say something about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Jenny Platt came and interviewed me, at great length, about that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 So something short w
ould be fine in that case? Well, how did it happen? Why did it interest you? What do you think you achieved?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
Well, as I said to you earlier, sociology had opened my eyes enormously, and explained all sorts of mysteries, which I was pleased to have ex
plained, and so I felt that it was right and proper to do what one could. Joe Banks asked me if I would go on to the Committee, and I think he must have been the person who said could he nominate me for Secretary or something? So I just got into those pos
itions. I worked with the women\rquote s caucus, about things to do with syllabuses that were masculinist, and things to do with jobs that weren\rquote t equally open, and things like that. I didn\rquote t find it, the job in general, a very happy one.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Well, r
eally because of the ghastly in-fighting between Marxists and others, which, in the greater scheme of things, seemed rather pointless. I suppose they were addressing material issues, but it seemed to me that - well, just let\rquote 
s say I was very uncomfortable with all of that stuff. I\rquote ve never been, formally, a Marxist, but I\rquote ve used a lot of those ideas in one way and another. And so I was pleased and proud to have done it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Because you became President, in the end, didn\rquote t you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Yes, I did. It\rquote s fairly honorary. You\rquote 
re supposed to give a Presidential Address, and you may get called on occasionally \endash  I don\rquote t think I was.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Were you trying to use the BSA to open up careers for women?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Well, yes. When I was working with the women\rquote s caucus, that\rquote 
s true. And there were other people on the Committee that were also interested in that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And did you see yourself as a model for younger women?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 They have told me, in hordes, since, that I was an important role model, and I\rquote m stil
l left with my mouth slightly falling open about this. I mean, it has to be true, because so many people have said this. I suppose I saw myself as pioneering in quite a lot of areas, not only gender, but other things like in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Methods of Social Research}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 ,
 and doing the kind of research I did, that we were talking about. But basically, I was just doing what seemed, to me, to be right, and however people saw it was, really, really their business. It\rquote s rather a piece, I suppose, of one saying, \'93
I never set out to have a career\'94, because that, you know, that wasn\rquote t something that I thought might be possible, really, or it certainly wasn\rquote t a high priority, it was something that would be nice to \'85 to do, if one could. But I hadn
\rquote t thought of a sort of career path. And in the same way, I, therefore, don\rquote 
t think I thought of myself, particularly, as a role model, although I knew that it was part of what I had to do, to support other women. And this I did whenever I could. Some Feminists, I noticed, really only used 
it for their own self-advancement, to my great shame. I always felt very ashamed about that. But I just determined I wasn\rquote t going to do that, so when I got a share, I just said that I would keep the faith. So I\rquote 
ve always supported any younger women who wanted help or were in trouble. But I wasn\rquote 
t thinking of myself as being a role model, I was thinking that I was a very lucky woman. Here I was, I had great doubts about whether I should ever have taken a Chair at all, in terms of what it meant in working in 
a hierarchy and things like that, so it bumped into one of my personal conflicts. But, no, I don\rquote t think I thought of myself as a role model, but I think I was one. (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 What do you mean about that remark you\rquote ve just made about working in a hierarchy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Well, I suppose I had egalitarian pretensions.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 You were just talking about working in a hierarchy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 That\rquote s right. I suppose I got increasingly unhappy about - I\rquote 
d always been unhappy, I suppose - about hierarchies, in the way peopl
e control others, and perhaps oppressively. I felt that by taking a role like being a professor, one was reinforcing that sort of hierarchy, and I suppose I partly felt it was okay if one subverted some of the rules of the game. Like I used to share infor
mation with the staff meetings, that not everybody would be happy to know that I was sharing. But it seemed right and proper. I mean, they were in this environment and they ought to know, and if they wanted to know, they should know. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9241263 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 But I just did have doubts, whereas I\rquote 
d tended to think, before \endash  and this might be the role model thing that you\rquote re talking about \endash 
 that I could show people a path, a way they could go, by just what I did, not what I said. I expect I wondered whether I was not demonstrating t
he wrong path, you know. But at the same time, when I first got the Chair, I can remember making quite certain that I was referred to as \'93Professor\'94, because as I used to say to people in shops, \'93No, not Mrs., Professor\'94, and they thought, 
\'93Oh-oh!\'94 So I said, \'93Well, I\rquote m doing this because people must learn that there are women who can be professors\'94
. And so I was, yes, in that sense, thinking of being a role model, in the sense I was trying to educate other people to this ghastly idea that you could have women in positions of relative power. (LAUGHS) Stupid isn\rquote 
t it! Funny games we play! (LAUGHS)
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11163676 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Mmm, it\rquote 
s quite complicated! Now, when you were not doing all this academic work, what sort of things did you do to enjoy yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Well, when I had all the children to raise, and I was doing all this academic work, there wasn\rquote 
t all that much time, but we used to go camping, and I greatly enjoyed that, and we used to go off for weekends sometimes. We lived by the sea, so we went on the beach, and that I enjoyed. I didn\rquote 
t play games, I never have played games, hated them at school. I didn\rquote t really have other hobbies. It was funny, when the kids started leaving home and I began to get time, I had to really teach myself how to read a novel again, because I hadn
\rquote t really had time to read novels. But I did succeed in doing that, I read plenty of novels. I mean, it was mostly, you know, mostly doing things with the family, I suppose, yes, that\rquote 
s right. And then, of course, these other activities, like going off to the Welsh Hospital Board, gave me journeys I wouldn\rquote t have otherwise taken, and meeting people I wouldn\rquote 
t have otherwise met. But I used to say, and I still stick by it, that my academic work was my recreation, I was doing it because I wanted to do it, and therefore, that was my recreation.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Politics, were you active?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 I have been a member of the Labour Party and was active at one time, but I don\rquote t think I wasn\rquote 
t active in the Labour Party in Banbury, and I wasn\rquote t in Swansea, it was really only early on.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
But before Banbury you were active? During that, I mean, you mentioned you were interested in politics in the War period, but after that, you weren\rquote t, no?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 I don\rquote t remember meetings of the Banbury Labour Party, for example. I don\rquote 
t think that was something that I did then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And then you were brought up as a Christian Scientist, but did you keep an interest in religion or not?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Not for many years, I suppose. I parted with that religion with sorrow, rather than with anger, unlike a lot of people who are very pleased to get out of whatever faith they
\rquote ve been brought up in, and it wasn\rquote t until I was in at least my sixties, probably seventies, that I had this sense that, in sociology, which, in a sense I\rquote d treated as a religio
n, I suppose, it was all very well, you could find out about all sorts of interesting things and uncover the causes of problems and this and that, but, you know, where do we go from here? So I felt a sort of discontent. And then I fell upon a book written
 by Thich Nhat Hanh, who\rquote s a Vietnamese peace exile, I don\rquote t know if you\rquote ve heard of him? He was a peace worker during the Vietnam War, and now they won\rquote 
t let him back in, the North thought he was working for the South, and the South thought he was working 
for the North, in which he was totally even-handed because he is that kind of person. I found that what he was writing was extremely illuminating, and so I\rquote ve followed that path, somewhat to my surprise. But it\rquote s interesting, and it\rquote 
s a very practical. I don\rquote t think it\rquote s a religion really, it\rquote s a lifestyle kind of a thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And what about long-term friendships, have they been important to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Yes. My closest woman friend from school, sadly enough, committed suicide not long before I came back t
o the Midlands, which was a great sorrow, because she lived in East Anglia, and I thought, \'93Well, at least I can see her more often now, I shall be half way there\'94
. But I do tend to keep friends, but I suppose close friends - too many of them have died, but you\rquote ll find any woman of my age will be saying that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 That\rquote s true. Would they be mainly also sociologists, or a great mixture, would you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Quite a lot sociologists, but not exclusively.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And men and women?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Yes, yes, but I think women more than men.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 And what about the age? They\rquote re mainly your age?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
Yes, although some are younger. Since when I got to Leamington, and I was still in the Labour Party, I was quite active in the Labour Party meetings there, and a bunch of us got together and, well, there always was a women\rquote 
s something at the Labour Party and we worked in that - where I can remember having great battles with Estelle Morris, who was of a different view. And there was a time when, collectively, we became the ag
ent for a candidate in the General Election, who did not get in, I may say. And those women, and some of them, even now, remain friends, are more like Jennifer\rquote 
s age than mine, and it was very nice that they always included me in their plans for, you know,
 when they got older or something, and not noticing that I was already there! (LAUGHS) Because Jennifer is 18 years younger than I am, and there were many around that age.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 So you have younger friends through her as well, presumably.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Yes, that\rquote s also true. Mmm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 So you were saying about being a role in trying to get other people to do things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Yeah, that\rquote s right. A role in helping people to, you know, get on and do
 what they want to. But beyond that, in the case, for example, of changing human reproduction, which whole issue came up in my later years, I took a role of encouraging other people and saying, \'93What are you sociologists doing that you aren\rquote 
t looking at these reproduction issues and these genetic issues?\'94 And there were plenty of people that supported this. So that\rquote s something I tried to do. And what I\rquote ve discovered is that, along the way, I\rquote 
ve encouraged people to do things I didn\rquote t know I was doing, I mean, just in the course of being myself and doing teaching and so on. So that\rquote s very nice to know! (LAUGHS) But I don\rquote t think there\rquote 
s anything else written down there that we haven\rquote t, one way or another, come upon.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Okay. Well, just to sum up, what would you say were the worst and the best things in your life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 Meg:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 
Oh, blimey! I hate questions like that! I think the worst things must have been people dying, especially unexpectedly, which most of the people close to me who have died, did die unexpectedly. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid544046\charrsid1901768 The best things? Well, there are so many of them! (LAUGHS) I mean, I just think that I\rquote 
m so lucky. Here I am with this nice house, and this nice garden, and I\rquote m still alive, and that\rquote s surprising! And for however long it lasts, it\rquote s nice while it lasts. And I\rquote 
ve just been so fortunate. In the course of my work I was able to travel, which I wouldn\rquote t have been able to do otherwise. I had interesting work. I had a family, and they\rquote re really great. They\rquote 
re all quite different from each other, they\rquote re all very independent, live their independent lives, and if any one of us is in trouble, they come together. So that\rquote s fine. They\rquote re scattered, but they come together when it\rquote 
s needed. One of the best things was taking up with Jennifer, because she\rquote s a very good companion, and we\rquote re very different, but we\rquote ve got a lot in common, and that was \'85 (LAUGHS) \'85 which I think it was that I\rquote 
d argued on the Senate for a Committee to look into what was then called \'93the position of women\'94, and they decided to have it, finally, and then they came after me to chair it, which you could expect, and I knew I couldn\rquote 
t do another single thing, so I asked Jennifer to do it. So that was really how I got to know her first. And then Terry Lovell set up an MA in Women\rquote s Studies, and I was the titular head, because they needed a professor to argue for them \endash 
 this hierarchical rubbish again \endash  and Jennifer was active in that. So that\rquote s one of the better things. But there have been lots and lots of best things.
\par 
